					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Everquest wizards guide through 18th level</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Eldwin</a> | 
		            11/17/1999 6:22:31 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2"><blockquote>
  <b><font size="+2">Everquest wizards guide through 18th level</font></b><br>
  <b>by Rhandom, on Tarrew Marr</b><br>
  <font size="2"><a href="http://www.thanesgames.com">www.thanesgames.com</a></font>
  <p><b>Wizard Overview</b>
  <p>Wizards are the most offense oriented casters in the game. Their damage
  spells typically can drop any enemy of their level in 3 to 4 casts (often with
  20 seconds), and they have powerful area effect spells than can kill several
  weaker enemies at once.
  <p>However, they are very weak defensively. They get the fewest HP of any
  class, and they get few protection spells or buffs, and no pets. As a wizard,
  your best defense will be a good offense. Some have claimed that wizards do
  not solo well for these reasons, but they are wrong - I have taken a wizard to
  15th level now and have only grouped for 1 or so level's worth of time. In
  fact, Rhandom made it all the way through 14th level without dying once
  (grouped for about 2 bubbles of EXP).
  <p>Wizards do excel in parties though. You are the "go to" guy in
  emergencies - you can drop an enemy in just a few seconds if needed. However,
  it is very important to let the party funtion. There is a strong temptation to
  burn the enemy as hard as you can during a combat - resist it. Your party
  doesn't want to wait for you to meditate after every con blue they fight
  because you wanted to nuke the enemy flat. They are quite capable of killing
  as well - it just takes them longer: )
  <p>Wizards don't have the money making potential of most caster classes, as
  they have few buffs which help other players. At later levels, you will be
  able to make a fair amount teleporting others about the world, as 5 to 10 pp
  per passenger is a typical rate for the service.
  <p>Play a wizard if you like the idea of standing back and blasting apart your
  enemies from a distance. Wizards are also a good choice if you want to play a
  caster but have connection problems - losing pet after pet because of slow
  phone lines can be very frustrating.
  <p><b>Starting your Wizard</b>
  <p>I have only played a human wizard, so my advice is directed towards them.
  Put as many of your points into intellegence, as this determines the amount of
  Mana you can store, which determines the number of spells you can cast before
  meditating. Where you put the remaining points isn't so critical - everything
  has tradeoffs.
  <p>Several people say you should only play gnome, erudite or elf wizards,
  because they can have a higher natural intelligence. Though they will be able
  to cast more spells at a time, they will also have to earn much more
  experience than you will per level  -those perks like infravision, hiding
  or 140 intelligence do come at a price. Futhermore, the number of kills they
  get in a given time will be the same as you, as you will still have the same
  meditation rate for mana recovery. They will have just a bit more reserve in a
  fight.
  <p>An important fact when buying jewelry later is that Intelligence increases
  your mana in increments of 5, so don't make your Int 112 - make it 110 or 115,
  or else the 2 points are not very useful. Go ahead an max out your
  intelligence at 119 or what ever with a starting character, as a lousy 3 pp
  ring gets you into the next increment of 5.
  <p>Put your first skill points into your primary weapon (1 hand peircing), and
  abjuration and alteration. A fun fact about skills is that  when you buy
  your first skill point in a given skill, it starts that skill at the level you
  currently are at. That means that if at level 12 you decide to take up
  brewing, your first poijnt of skill purchased will actually put you at level
  12 skill. So, don't put any points into any skill until you are ready to
  actually use that skill. Thus put no points into conjuration until you buy a
  spell that requires conjuration (probably at level 8 or 12).
  <p>With that, go out and blast some rats and stuff. Stay near the guards! Try
  to replace that dagger with a cracked staff or Giant Snake Fang as soon as you
  can. Save those bone chips and batwings, as they can easilly be sold for 1 to
  3 pp a stack to higher level casters with more important things to do than
  kill wimpy creatures for reagents.
  <p><b>Soloing your wizard</b>
  <p>Wizards can solo very well, based on 3 different tactics - blast and fight,
  root and nuke, or kiting (some people don't think wizards can kite!).
  <p><u>Blast and fight</u> - The worst choice, but typically all you have got,
  especillay until you get the root spell. Pick an isolated target, try to
  maximize the distance between yourselves, and hit it with the biggest spell
  you got. Then, while it is running towards you, hit it again. It ought to be
  below half damage by the time it reaches you, so you have a good advantage in
  the melee. Once you are fighting, time your nuking spells so you start casting
  right after they take a swing at you. Most monsters have a delay between
  strikes of about 2 seconds, so you have that much time to get a spell off
  before he has a chance to hit you again. Also, don't throw out those lower
  level spells - while they do less damage than your shiny new ones, they also
  take much less time to cast. If you can't seem to get off your shock of
  lightning between getting hit, use your shock of ice, or even shock of fire.
  <p>When you get an enemy to 1 bubble of health, and no other threats are near,
  go ahead and let your melee attacks finish him off. You want to give your
  melee skills a chance to increase, because they can save you when you run out
  of mana. But if something ugly is near, or your enemy is running to fast from
  you, just nuke him. No sense running into his big brother when you've just
  used half of your mana on him.
  <p>This tactic becomes less and less effective as you gain levels - the
  creatures will be able to kill you even if they are at 1/4 health and you are
  at full by the time the melee starts. I would say only use this on weak con
  blues after 12th level.
  <p><u>Root and nuke</u> - This is what wizards are best known for -  a
  root spell holds the enemy in place, while you nuke it from a safe distance.
  <p>    However, it rarely works so well. Often the creature
  resists and charges you, with the effect of turning the combat into a melee
  against a full strength monster. Sometimes it will also break free after
  taking damage (there is a chance it will break free after any damage spell
  hits it). Root is very ineffective against creatures bigger than you (don't
  waste your time against a creature that cons red).
  <p>    This is my least used tactic - I only use it if there is
  a zone nearby, against a creature that can poison or disease me. Root costs a
  good chunk of mana, which I would rather have available to blast  away
  with. Too often, I have rooted something and run out of mana in the fight when
  I really wanted it (see the section on bugging out). I'm sure this will become
  less of an issue with my level 5 spells, as the cost of root is less and less
  significant with the more mana you have. Root and blast became more effective
  to me after level 15.
  <p>    <u>Kiting</u> - Kiting is a very viable ability for
  wizards -  we can easily kill a con yellow if we start with full mana.
  Kiting usually require a Spirit of Wolf purchase from a shaman or druid, so be
  nice to them! I make it a point to always help out a shaman or druid  if
  I see them struggling, as often you can get a free spell out of them. They are
  great allies for a wizard.
  <p>    You can also kite slow creatures without a SoW,
  specifically beetles of all sizes.
  <p>    Kiting works this way: you blast the enemy with your
  heaviest spell, then you run away from it. When you get a bit of distance on
  it, you stop and blast it again. 3 or 4 repeats, and it is dead, with you not
  getting scratched. The "Shock" spells are the best for this tactic -
  they do not need a line of sight, so you can easily attack things behind you;
  they also take less time than the bolt spells.
  <p>    There are 2 important considerations. The first is that
  it takes an aggrevatingly long time to come to a complete stop when running,
  letting the creature get too close to you while you are casting, or disrupting
  your concentration because you tried to cast too early. There is a simple way
  to avoid this - while your forward motion has a slow down time associated with
  it, your turning time does not. When you want to stop to cast the spell,
  release the forward key and press the turn key just for a second - this
  immediately stops your forward motion, and when you release the turn key it
  also stops. Now you are still and serene, and can blast a spell. Also,
  stopping is a lot harder going down hill, so I try to avoid casting when I am
  kiting down a hill.
  <p>    Secondly, you don't want to run into a second creature
  while the first is alive, so plan where you will be running, and don't be
  afraid to turn around and run the other way when something is ugly up ahead.
  Taking a hit or two from the guy chasing you is a lot better than getting
  another creature on you.
  <p>    If you run out of mana before your enemy dies, but it is
  close, you can turn and fight it. This is still a bad idea after level 12, so
  there is a high risk tactic that works if you are SoW'd : run way ahead, sit
  and med until the monster sounds close, get up and run ahead again, repeat.
  When you get enough mana, kill it. I've killed many things after a bout of
  fizzles and resists but - NEVER DO THIS IF YOU ARE SUFFERING ANY LAG AT
  ALL!!!!!!
  <p><b>Fighting in Groups</b>
  <p>    Group fighting is a lot different, and every group will
  have its strengths and weaknesses that you must adjust to. So here's just a
  few pointers.
  <p>    Let the fighters pull a creature if you can. Creatures
  hate getting blasted right from the start and sometimes nothing anyone else
  does will turn that creature from you- meaning you can't get off your best
  spells, and you may die before the creature is killed. That sucks.
  <p>    Area of effect spells are great when your party is
  fighting several things at once - often you can damage 3 or more creatures at
  once. But be carefull - if those creatures have not been damage by someone
  else yet, they may turn on you with the effect listed as above. Use the rain
  spells when several enemies are engaged by various party members, who have had
  a chance to do a few hits already.
  <p>    Watch the life meters. If one person seems to be getting
  beat on, nuke his enemy hard. Mana regenerates a lot faster than a fighters
  HP's and losing a party member always sucks.
  <p>    Don't just stand around. Don't be afraid to improve your
  combat skills by jumping into the fray against an otherwise occupied enemy.
  But get out of there if he turns on you - you've got a lot fewer HP than that
  fighter, and you are no good to anyone dead. Also, don't be afraid to med if
  you are low on mana during a fight while your party is still strong. It's
  always fun to stand up and delivcer the killing blow when the party is just
  about spent.
  <p>    If you are meditating, and something weak and stupid
  attacks the party that they can easily handle, just keep medding. You will be
  much more useful with full mana later than against an enemy that had no chance
  against the party to begin with. One fun thing is to let a lower level
  character hang around outside of the party to get the weak things - he gets
  exp for the weak stuff, and the protection of the group if he gets in trouble.
  You get to meditiate in peace.
  <p>    Against enemy healers, save your burn spells until he is
  below 1/3 health. Then nuke him with all you got. Nothing is more aggrevating
  than watching an orc shaman heal itself time after time while your party beats
  on it.
  <p>    One fun thing to try is the all Wizard party. Near the
  Orcs in the Oasis, 5 of us stood on a dune - we would pick an enemy, 5 wizards
  would cast lightning bolts at it, and 5 seconds later it was dead. It was the
  ultimate artillery battery.
  <p><b>Bugging out (the fine art of running away)</b>
  <p>    Ok, that Con White you were sure was easy pickings has
  resisted 3 of your spells, and you are below half mana without wounding him at
  all. Time to get away.
  <p>    You must realize that there are some fights that you
  just won't be able to win. So go for the draw, by running away. At low levels,
  stay near the zone boundaries and guards, and decide how much damage you can
  take that will still let you get to them without dying. And obey that limit -
  the loss of a few minutes to heal and not getting the EXP for the kill is
  nothing compared to the time it takes to rememorize your spells and retrieve
  your corpse, and you can lose many kills worth of experience from one death.
  <p>    The absolute most useful escape spells are Shadow Step
  and Gate.  Don't bother using the weaker Dimension Door spell, as it will
  not get you far enough away to matter. Shadow Step takes 1 second to cast,
  meaning you can easily time it between enemy attacks. It will teleport you a
  random distance and direction, sometimes quite far. If you are still too
  close, cast it again. Once you get 4 seconds away from the enemy, cast Gate.
  <p>    Don't try to cast gate in a melee - it takes almost 4
  seconds, meaning your enemy will get 2 chances to disrupt it. Even if you
  don't have enough mana for the gate, Shadow Step can give you enough distance
  that you can make a zone or guard, or beg for help from someone nearby.
  Sometimes you can be teleported outside of the aggro range of the creature,
  meaning he stops trying to follow you. However, he will hate you until he dies
  or you zone out, so if you wander back into his aggro range he will charge you
  again.
  <p>    A second choice that often works is to root the enemy,
  then back out of the combat. Sometimes you will be able to back far away, with
  enough mana to try blasting the enemy again - just give yourself enough
  distance that you still have options if the enemy breaks free. Roots are
  almost entirely ineffective against things that con red to you - shadow step
  is a better choice in that case.
  <p>    In a group, realize you don't have to go down with the
  ship. You will typically have time to look around, and can tell when things
  look bad. Tell your party things look bad, and if you have the mana, root a
  few of the enemy so the party has a better chance of escaping.. If your party
  insists on fighting ot the last man, don't be embarassed to bug out on your
  own - if they get mad and kick you out for it, remind yourself that these guys
  were stupid, and would probably have cost you a lot of time and EXP if you
  played their game.<br>
   <br>
   
</blockquote>


			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
